  "correctAnswer": "D",
  "section": "Math",
  "steps": [
    {
      "title": "Set up",
      "content": "Expand and collect: $x(x+9) - 15 = 0$ becomes $x^2 + 9x - 15 = 0$. So $a = 1$, $b = 9$, $c = -15$."
    },
    {
      "title": "Solve",
      "content": "Compute the discriminant: $b^2 - 4ac = 81 - 4(1)(-15) = 81 + 60 = 141$. Substitute: $$x = \\frac{-9 \\pm \\sqrt{141}}{2}$$"
    },
    {
      "title": "Answer",
      "content": "<strong>D</strong> is correct. The discriminant is not a perfect square, so the two solutions must remain in radical form with denominator $2a=2$."
    }
  ]
}
